      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Walk-Run — Foot Check\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a brisk 3-minute walk at a comfortable pace. This is not optional — it primes the plantar fascia and Achilles before any running load is applied.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the easier end of your easy pace range (5:45–5:58/km). If you feel any foot pain — even a 1 out of 10 — transition immediately to walking. No heroics today. The goal is sensation monitoring, not distance.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk out the final 3 minutes. After stopping, take 2 minutes to gently stretch your calf and roll your foot on a frozen water bottle if available.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 minutes of easy walking before any running begins. This is your foot's early warning system — pay attention to any tightness, sharp sensation, or pulling in the heel or arch.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes to let your heart rate settle naturally. Avoid standing still immediately after stopping. A gentle calf stretch held for 30 seconds each side is a good habit to build now.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, welcome back. This first run of the week is less about fitness and more about listening. Your physio has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running, and that clearance came with conditions — walking breaks if there's any foot pain. Honor that. Your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 tells us you have real fitness underneath, but plantar fasciitis responds poorly to impatience. The easy pace range here is 5:24–5:58/km; aim for the slower end (5:45–5:58) for now. Building a reliable return is the win this week — not the pace, not the distance.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run — Building Consistency\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk briskly for 3 minutes. Pay close attention to how the right foot feels before you begin running. If there's any morning stiffness carryover from Tuesday, give yourself an extra minute of walking.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":14,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run easy and conversational — if you couldn't hold a sentence, you're going too fast. Stay at 5:45–5:58/km. If foot discomfort appears, drop to a walk immediately without frustration. Walking during this phase is not a setback; it's the plan working correctly.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 minutes of easy walking. Do your calf and plantar stretches again. Consistency with these post-run habits compounds over the weeks ahead.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of walking. Notice how the foot feels compared to Tuesday — is it better, similar, or more tender? That comparison is useful information to share with your physio.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3 minutes, then gentle calf stretches and plantar fascia stretch (pulling toes back toward shin). Keep notes on how the foot felt — even a quick word or two on your phone helps track progress over time.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek run is about building the habit of consistency at low load. Two runs this week with one more on Saturday is exactly the right structure for a return-from-injury phase. Your recent weeks show you've been doing 2–3 runs, which is a good foundation to build on. The physiological goal right now is tendon and connective tissue adaptation — that happens slowly, through repeated low-stress loading, not through pushing pace or distance. There is no speed work in this plan yet; that door will open once your physio gives the green light and the foot consistently tolerates easy running without complaint.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Long Run — Easy & Exploratory\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 4 minutes before running begins. This is your longest run of the week — a more deliberate warmup respects that. Feel the foot carefully during the walk. No rushing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at the easy end of your pace range, 5:45–5:58/km. This is your 'long run' in the context of where you are right now — and that's valid. If foot pain appears at any point, walk immediately. You can alternate walking and running if needed: 5 minutes running, 2 minutes walking works well if the foot is protesting.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 4 minutes. This is a longer cooldown than the midweek runs because Saturday carries slightly more load. After the walk, do your full post-run routine: calf stretch, plantar stretch, and elevate the foot for a few minutes if possible.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"4-minute walk warmup. On Saturdays, take a moment before you start to check in with yourself — how did the foot feel this morning when you got out of bed? First-step pain in the morning is a classic plantar fasciitis signal worth noting and reporting to your physio.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"4 minutes of walking, then calf stretches, plantar fascia stretches, and foot elevation for 5 minutes if possible. If the foot feels more tender than usual after this run, apply ice for 10–15 minutes and consider whether Tuesday's run should begin with more walking. Always err toward caution.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day, and right now that means the same 20-minute cap — but with a slightly extended warmup and cooldown to account for it being the week's biggest effort. The goal of the long run in a return-from-injury block isn't to build aerobic base; it's to validate that the foot can handle three days of loading without accumulating distress. If you complete this run with no foot pain, that's a genuinely meaningful win. Your weekly volume this week will be around 10 km, which aligns with your recent weeks and respects the 10% progression cap. No speed work, no pushing pace, no chasing your pre-injury fitness. That fitness is still in there — the job right now is to give the foot the environment it needs to let you access it again.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
